Denote spherical coordinates as $(\rho,\theta,\phi),$ and let be $(\rho,\theta,\phi)$ spherical coordinates of said point. Then, from these coordinates we obtain rectangular coordinates as
\begin{align*}
(x, y, z) &= (\rho \sin \theta \cos \phi, \rho \sin \theta \sin \phi, \rho \cos \theta), \hspace{1cm} (A)
\end{align*}
where 
\begin{align*}
\rho^2 &= x^2 + y^2 + z^2 \\
0 &\le \theta \le \pi, \\
0 &\le \phi \le 2 \pi.
\end{align*}
Given rectangular coordinates in $(A),$ we obtain the following piece of Cartesian coordinates:
\begin{align*}
(x, y, -z) &= (\rho \sin \theta \cos \phi, \rho \sin \theta \sin \phi, -\rho \cos \theta) \\
&= (\rho \sin \theta \cos \phi, \rho \sin \theta \sin \phi, -1 \cdot \rho \cos \theta).
\end{align*}
From this we can obtain spherical coordinates. Note that the value for $\phi$ is  $\pi - \phi$ since the fifth coordinate on the right-hand side went from positive to negative. In addition, the value for $\theta$ is $\pi + \phi$ as $-1$ in the spherical coordinates corresponds to $\pi$ radians from the line of the coordinate axes since $\phi = \frac{2 \pi}{7},$ as is the given radius, $\rho.$ Then, we have the following from $(A)$ to obtain rectangular coordinates:
\begin{align*}
(\rho \sin \theta \cos \phi, \rho \sin \theta \sin \phi, -\rho \cos \theta) &= (\rho \sin \theta \cos \phi, \rho \sin \theta \sin \phi, -1 \cdot \rho \cos \theta) \\
(\rho \sin \theta \cos \phi, \rho \sin \theta \sin \phi, \rho \cos \theta) &= (\rho \sin \theta \cos \phi, \rho \sin \theta \sin \phi, \rho (-\cos \theta)).
\end{align*}
Then, the spherical coordinates of the point with rectangular coordinates $(x, y, -z)$ are
\begin{align*}
(\rho, \theta, \pi - \phi).
\end{align*}
</think> Finally, the answer is $\boxed{\left(2, \pi + \frac{2 \pi}{7}, \frac{5 \pi}{9} \right)}.$ $ \ \square$
